#week-title("Two", "Water Distillation: Melissa Hydrosol & Oil")

=== Core Teaching

This week, perform the water distillation of your Melissa. The goal is to
produce the *hydrosol* (Melissa water) and, if possible, separate any essential
oil that forms a layer.

Each stage of the distillation has an exact philosophical meaning. The alchemist
observes the "first spirit" that rises, noting its scent and clarity. The oil
layer represents the plant's Sulphur, freed from its matrix.

#lab[
  *Distillation Protocol*
  + *Charge the flask* with Melissa and distilled water.
  + *Assemble the train:* ensure all seals are luted or tight.
  + *Apply gentle heat:* monitor the thermometer.
  + *Collect the distillate:* watch for changes in turbidity and scent.
  + *Separate the oil:* use a separator funnel or pipette if an oily layer
    appears.
]

=== Topics This Week

- Practical distillation of Melissa officinalis
- Identifying the hydrosol and oil fraction
- Monitoring the condensation rhythm

#inner-work[
  *Desoille's Dawn: The Albedo*

  Distillation in the laboratory corresponds to the transition Robert Desoille
  calls the *Dawn* — the point where the subject, having descended through the
  darkness, begins to ascend toward the light. This is the *Albedo* (the
  whitening).

  *The Practice:*
  Sit in meditation. Conduct a short waking dream. Begin from wherever your
  previous descending movement left off. Allow the imagery to move — do not
  force it upward, but note if it naturally lightens. Record the quality of the
  images.
]

